ANU op 
The ANY operator compares a value with the values returned by a subquery. The condition is true if it matches at least one value returned by the subquery.

SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name operator ANY (
    SELECT column_name
    FROM table_name
);
example 

SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE salary < ANY (
    SELECT salary
    FROM Employee
    WHERE dept_id = 102
);


select emp_name, city  from Employee
where salary > any (select salary from Employee where dept_id= 101);


---------------------------------------------------------------------------

ALL

The ALL operator in MySQL compares a value with all values returned by a subquery. The condition is true only 
if it satisfies the comparison with every value in the subquery.

SELECT column_name
FROM table_name
WHERE column_name operator ALL (
    SELECT column_name
    FROM table_name
);

Salary Greater Than All Employees in Department 101
select * from Employee where salary > all (select salary from Employee where dept_id =101);

Salary Less Than All Employees in Department 102
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE salary < ALL (
    SELECT salary
    FROM Employee
    WHERE dept_id = 102
);


Difference Between ANY and ALL
ANY                                                                     	ALL
Condition must be true for at least one value	              Condition must be true for every value
Similar to "any one"	                                      Similar to "all of them"

